{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496633"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:52:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:52:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1398"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1398"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.09,0.07,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109036"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1398"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40716"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109036"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man has an abdominal CT scan performed after an episode of left iliac fossa pain which was thought to be due to diverticulitis. The CT scan confirms this diagnosis, showing a thickened sigmoid colon and several diverticulae. It also shows a 4.5 cm abdominal aortic aneurysm which is assessed as being an incidental finding. The patient is now symptom-free. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"With regards to the aneurysm, which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Annual ultrasound assessment","Two-yearly CT scan review","Elective endovascular repair","Elective open repair","Pharmacological intervention"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAlthough there is variation in the international guidelines for the surveillance of asymptomatic abdominal aortic aneurysms (AAAs), the 2024 European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) guidelines are most widely followed, including in Australia and New Zealand. The ESVS guidelines recommend the following monitoring schedule for asymptomatic patients according to AAA diameter:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E25 - 29 mm: ultrasound every five years\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E30 - 39 mm: ultrasound every three years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E40 - 49 mm (men) \u003C/strong\u003Eor 40 \u2013 44 mm (women):\u003Cstrong\u003E annual ultrasound\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226550 mm (men) or \u226545 mm (women): ultrasound every six months.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226555 mm (men) or \u226550 mm (women): most surgeons would consider offering surgical repair; note that the threshold for elective repair in women is lower due to higher rupture risk at smaller diameters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that these are general guidelines, and different monitoring protocols may be utilised for patients with AAAs based on clinician judgement and patient factors (e.g. life expectancy, suitability for future repair, patient preferences).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of rupture of a 4.5 cm abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) is remote and less than 1% of over the following twelve months. This patient as per these guidelines therefore needs an annual ultrasound assessment of his AAA. A\u003Cstrong\u003E CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E would only be performed if intervention was considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn aneurysm greater than 5.5 cm should be considered for \u003Cstrong\u003Eelective\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eendovascular repair\u003C/strong\u003E and if that patient is unsuitable for such an approach, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eelective\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eopen repair\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered, both of which would be excessive at this stage for this patient. With regards to \u003Cstrong\u003Epharmacological interventions\u003C/strong\u003E, animal trials have shown reduction in growth of aneurysms, but this has not been proven in humans. Good cardiovascular risk factor management is important and this includes weight reduction, statin use and smoking cessation. Medical therapies such as doxycycline, beta blockers, statins and angiotensin II receptor blockers have no proven worth. First degree relatives should be screened for AAA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aneurysms of \u003C55 mm in men can be kept under regular (ultrasound) surveillance."],"references":["ESVS 2024 Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm. In: European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://esvs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/ESVS-2024-AAA-Guidelines.pdf","Olson SL, Wijesinha MA, Panthofer AM, Blackwelder WC, Upchurch GR Jr, Terrin ML, et al. Evaluating Growth Patterns of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm Diameter With Serial Computed Tomography Surveillance. JAMA Surg. 2021;156(4):363-370. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7890454/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1398"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:14:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:40:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1398"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109036"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"175","links":{"self":"htt